A separate class `Recipe` should be implemented, including receipt name, a collection of ingredients, set of instructions what should be done with the ingredients.  

In its turn, the receipt ingredients should contain information about the food, amount, and measurement unit of amount (pieces, grams/ounces, tablespoons/teaspoons, etc.).  Food may be represented as a `String` value for simplicity, or as a class/enum with more details (e.g. category, price, preparation, possible replacements, etc.)
```java
public class Ingredient {
    String food;
    Number amount;
    Unit unit;

// constructor(s), getters/setters
}

enum Unit {
    PIECE,
    GRAM,
    MILLILITER,
    TABLESPOON,
    TEASPOON;
}
``` 
The question _what is the best way of implementation_ of the ingredient collection per recipe is actually an opinion-based one.  It may be done as a map:
```java
public class Recipe {
    String name;
    Map&lt;String, Ingredient&gt; ingredientsByNames;
    String instructions;
// constructor(s), getters/setters
}
``` 
or a list/set:
```java
public class Recipe {
    String name;
    List&lt;Ingredient&gt; ingredients;
    String instructions;
// constructor(s), getters/setters
