You don&#39;t have to specify how many times the loop has to execute - to be exact, you shouldn&#39;t as the instructions ask you to read integers till a negative integer is read. You can just use `do { ... } while (..);` and have it run as many times as needed.

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Max {
   
   public int findMax() {
   
   Scanner scnr = new Scanner(System.in);
      int maxSoFar = 0;
      int currValue;

      do {
         currValue = scnr.nextInt();

         if (currValue &gt; maxSoFar) {
            maxSoFar = currValue;
         }
      } while (currValue &gt;= 0);
      
      return maxSoFar;
      
   }
   
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Max test = new Max();
      System.out.println(test.findMax());
   }
}
```

You&#39;re almost there. You&#39;ve to add 2 things.

 - Take input until user gives negative number
 - Output `error` when there&#39;s only one input (although, you didn&#39;t mention the error case clearly, I&#39;m assuming this from the input)

Take input until user gives negative number:

In your code you&#39;re taking input `numValues` time. Which you initialized with `5`.

So basically you&#39;re taking `5` inputs.

To take input until you&#39;re given a negative number, you can do like below:

    while(1)
    {
        currValue = scnr.nextInt();
        if(currValue &lt; 0) break;
        else
        {
            // do the rest of the task
        }
    }

Output error when there&#39;s only one input:

You can keep a `counter` of how many valid inputs you&#39;ve taken so far.
If `count &lt;= 1`, then you&#39;ll show `error` as output.

Overall code:

    import java.util.Scanner;
    
    public class Max
    {
        public int findMax()
        {
            Scanner scnr = new Scanner(System.in);
            int maxSoFar = 0;
            int currValue;
            int validInputCounter = 0;
    
            while(1)
            {
                currValue = scnr.nextInt();
                if(currValue &lt; 0) break;
                else
                {
                    validInputCounter++;
    
                    if (validInputCounter == 1)   // First iteration
                    {
                        maxSoFar = currValue;
                    }
                    else if (currValue &gt; maxSoFar)
                    {
                        maxSoFar = currValue;
                    }
                }
            }
    
            if (validInputCounter &lt;= 1)
            {
                return -1;
            }
    
            return maxSoFar;
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args)
        {
            Max test = new Max();
    
            int maxValue = test.findMax();
    
            if(maxValue == -1) System.out.println(&quot;Error&quot;);
            else System.out.println(maxValue);
        }
    }

You only need to compare `currValue` and `maxSoFar`. Like this,

```
public class Max {

    public int findMax() {
        Scanner scnr = new Scanner(System.in);
        int maxSoFar = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        int numValues = 5;

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; numValues; ++i) {
            int currValue = scnr.nextInt();

            if (currValue &gt; maxSoFar) {
                maxSoFar = currValue;
            }
        }

        return maxSoFar;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Max test = new Max();
        System.out.println(test.findMax());
    }
}
```

